comments.text:
That scene where Bartleby teaches Manic a lesson is very powerful.

Usually the sentiment for a love not returned is either of the following:
"just keep trying to win him over, you go girl"
"don't accept a no for an answer, you can win his heart"
"i was in your position one time, you'll get through it"
"let me get you a BEER"

But more often than not, this breeds BAD things: stalkers, harassers, abusers
As the object of desire, being bombarded with some creeps love messages and confessions after you told them NO is very stressful.

Tamers goes the opposite direction and teaches us a new sentiment:
"get your shit together, hes not interested"
"fuck off and die if you cannot accept that they aren't interested in you"
"you are the cancer that makes us all suffer, unless you cut yourself out of our lives we will do it for you"

Perhaps imbued with experience of something like this, Tamers brings new ideas to the table, at least for what i see in the media.

You know, at first i struggled to understand Bartleby's motivations and why he was unable to comprehend Manic's plight about him and his brothers relationship. But after re-watching this a few times i finally understand, Bartleby full-well knew what Manic was going through, Bartleby himself went through a  similar situation with his parents,  and while Bartleby was strong enough to accept the reality of him and parents relationship - Manic isn't. Which is why Bartleby took the picture from Manic, as it would only cause him to mull over the past and thus never be able to move on. I've seen some people in the comment section say that Bartleby took it way too far, and while he was blunt about it, you have to remember that Bartleby grew up very sheltered and has always floundered in social and emotional situations. Bartleby did the best he could do,, it's not his fault that Manic is retarded and has to be beaten like a bitch for him to understand.

comments.text: Actually Bartelby was pretty on the nose about this sort of issue. Years ago when I was hung up on a group of friends, my therapist had to have a talk with me about this sort of thing.
